https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/markets/four-investment-bets-from-a-fund-manager-who-delivered-93-return-over-the-past-year-12607781.html,"He may be a lesser-known investment manager, but his track record over the past year certainly demonstrates a winning streak. Based in Gurugram, Siddharth Oberoi of Prudent Equity AIF manages a Category III Alternate Investment Fund. Since its inception in December 2022, his fund has yielded a return of 62.94 percent compared to its benchmark S&P 500 at 20.85 percent. In the last year alone, the fund has delivered a return of 93 percent compared to the benchmark of 38 percent. He spoke exclusively to Moneycontrol about his top investment picks. Home finance – Proxy for real estate surgeOberoi suggests investors play the real estate theme through housing finance companies rather than directly because valuations of real estate companies have skyrocketed and are now fully valued. The Nifty Realty Index has a trailing PE of 61.5x as of April 8, which was 38.2x a year ago.  On the contrary, housing finance companies are being overlooked and are undervalued, he notes. “Almost 90 percent of real estate purchases are financed and currently the demand for real estate is strong, so the outlook for housing finance companies appears bright,” Oberoi says. ""The demand is so strong that 80 percent of the flats in a new project get booked on the first day itself."" The best way to benefit from this surge in demand, which he feels is largely restricted to the luxury segment, is through housing financiers. Housing finance companies contribute 15 percent to the overall fund's portfolio. Broadcast companies: Bet on election splurgeHis views on the broadcasting sector are positive in the short term and negative in the long run. Oberoi believes that advertising revenues of broadcasting companies may surge due to the election season, making it a good bet in the short term. However, he believes these are not good long-term investment bets due to intense competition in the sector and unappealing growth prospects. Also read :Media stocks soar amid election advertisement spending boom Time Technoplast: Undervalued growthThe fund manager is currently bullish on Time Technoplast and Welspun Enterprises. He purchased Time Technoplast shares when the company announced its plan to become debt-free and distribute the leftover from overseas business to its shareholders. ""Now the company is paying off its debt by selling low-margin and low-ROE businesses,"" said Oberoi. Time Technoplast is a well-diversified company with multiple verticals and plans to focus on their India business and selling the overseas one. The retained vertical is also higher margin one and will make the company more capital efficient. Plus it is highly undervalued for a company growing at 15 percent annually. Welspun Enterprises: Cash is comfortOberoi likes Welspun Enterprises because it has a lot of cash on its books and extremely low debt. The company is also very selective in taking projects. It does not take projects until a certain margin requirement is met. It has also monetized all its assets. Also, it has an order book of Rs 14,000 crore, executable over the next three years. Also, the company is trading at single digit P/E multiples. Oberoi’s investment thesis focuses on individual businesses and their growth prospects rather than the macro story. He also prefers buying stocks in special situations like buybacks or open offers. The fund manager says, ""A company doing a series of buybacks suggests that it has a good capital allocation policy, especially when done at a cheap price. Buybacks are a significant trigger for stock prices as it means that the company is sucking out liquidity from the market, plus it is EPS (earnings per share) accretive."" Disclaimer:The views and investment tips expressed by experts on Moneycontrol.com are their own and not those of the website or its management. Moneycontrol.com advises users to check with certified experts before taking any investment decisions.​​​
